<paragraph blockId="33.[178,1086,655,824]" pageId="33" pageNumber="966">
The gender of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="FABRICIUS" authorityYear="1804" box="[441,489,656,677]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Liris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="966" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[441,489,656,677]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="966">Liris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is feminine according to 
<bibRefCitation author="FABRICIUS I" box="[753,939,656,678]" pageId="33" pageNumber="966" refId="ref50801" refString="FABRICIUS I. C. (1804): Systema Piezatorum. - Braunschweig (K. REICHARD): 440 pp + 28 pp." type="book" year="1804">FABRICIUS (1804)</bibRefCitation>
, because a lot of species names are ending with –a (ICZN Article 30.2.2). As FABRICIUS lived several years in Paris, the name probably derives from the French word &quot;l’iris&quot; (flower iris). I don’t follow MENKE &amp; BOHART (1979: Proceedings of the Entomological Society 81 (1): 117), that the genus name derives from the latin name of the river Garigliano and the gender is masculine (see above).
</paragraph>
